# 🏔️ Image → Height Map → Normal Map → 3D Terrain Mesh

> Transform any flat 2D image into a fully exportable 3D terrain mesh and tangent-space normal map — using pure Python and open-source libraries.
> check pdf: ''terrain generator.pdf'' for understanding the project in detail.

---

## 📸 What It Does

| Input :Any `.png` / `.jpg` / `.bmp` image 
| output :`terrain.obj` — 3D mesh (Blender, Unity, Unreal ready)

| Bright pixels → high elevation 
|`normal_map.png` — RGB-encoded surface normals 
| Dark pixels → low elevation 
|Live 3D matplotlib preview 

| **No input file?** 

The script auto-generates a demo terrain with hills and noise so you can see the full pipeline immediately.

---

## 🗺️ Pipeline Overview

```
Input Image (any photo)
        │
        ▼
 Luminance Extraction

    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2LAB) 

        |
        ▼
 Gaussian Smoothing  ──→  Height Map
 (removes noise/spikes)
        │
        ├─────────────────────────┐
        ▼                         ▼
 Sobel Gradient               Grid of XYZ vertices
 ∂h/∂x,  ∂h/∂y                X = col / (cols-1)
        │                      Y = row / (rows-1)
        ▼                      Z = np.power(hmap,gamma)*HEIGHT_SCALE
 N = (−∂h/∂x, −∂h/∂y, 1)              │
 normalise → unit vector               ▼
        │                    Quad Triangulation
        ▼                    2 triangles per cell
  normal_map.png              terrain.obj  +  UV map
```

---

## ⚙️ Installation

 1. Open the VS Code terminal
Press **Ctrl + `` ` ``** to open the integrated terminal.

 2. Install all dependencies (one command)
```bash
 pip install -r requirements.txt
```

> If you have multiple Python versions, use `python -m pip install ...` instead.

3. Verify Python version
```bash
python --version   # needs Python 3.8 or newer
```

---

## 🚀 Quick Start

```bash
# Run with the auto-generated demo terrain
python terrain_mesh_generator.py

# Run with your own image
# → place your image in the same folder, then set INPUT_IMAGE in the script
python terrain_mesh_generator.py input.png
```

**Outputs appear in the same folder as the script:**
```
terrain_mesh_generator.py
terrain.obj          ← 3D mesh
normal_map.png       ← normal map
```

---

## 🎛️ Configuration

Open `terrain_mesh_generator.py` and edit the constants at the top:

```python
INPUT_IMAGE   = "input.png"   # path to your source image
OUTPUT_MESH   = "terrain.obj" # output 3D mesh filename
OUTPUT_NORMAL = "normal_map.png"  # output normal map filename

MESH_WIDTH    = 128    # grid columns  (64 = fast/blocky · 512 = detailed/slow)
MESH_HEIGHT   = 128    # grid rows
HEIGHT_SCALE  = 20.0   # max elevation (5 = subtle · 50 = dramatic mountains)
SMOOTH_SIGMA  = 1.5    # blur radius   (0 = off · 3.0 = smooth rolling hills)
```

| Parameter | Low value | High value |
|---|---|---|
| `MESH_WIDTH/HEIGHT` | 64 → fast, coarse | 512 → slow, detailed |
| `HEIGHT_SCALE` | 5 → flat terrain | 50 → tall mountains |
| `SMOOTH_SIGMA` | 0 → spiky/raw | 3.0 → smooth hills |

